4. What are the values of the following expressions?
(5 > 4) and (3 == 5) -> False
not (5 > 4)  -> False
(5 > 4) or (3 == 5) -> True
not ((5 > 4) or (3 == 5)) -> False
(True and True) and (True == False) -> False
(not False) or (not True) -> True

5. What are the six comparison operators?
i) == Equals operator this operator will compare values from both side.
   5 == 5 -> this will return True
   5 == 4 -> this will return False
ii) > Greater than Operator, This operator will compare the left side value with right side value.
    10 > 5 -> This will return True
    10 < 20 -> This will return False
iii) < less Than Operator, This opeartor will compare left side value with right side value.
    6 < 8 -> This will return True
    8 < 10 -> This will return False
iv) <= Less Than Equal to , This opeartor will check if left side value is less than or equal to the right side value
    4 <= 3 -> This will return false
    6 <= 10 -> This will return True
    8 <= 8 -> This will return True
v) >= Greater than equal to, This operator will check if left side value is greater than or equal to right side value.
   5 >= 10 -> This will return False
   7 >= 4 -> This will return True
   6 >= 6 -> This will return True
vi) != Not Equal to, This operator will check if the values are equal to or not
    7 != 6 -> This will return True
    8 != 8 -> This will return False
    
6. How do you tell the difference between the equal to and assignment operators?Describe a
condition and when you would use one.
Assignment(=) operator is used to assgin a value to the variable
But in equal to operator (==) we are comparing left side value with right side value.
If I just want to initialize a variable with any value i Will use Assignment operator. -> num = 10
If I want to compare thw two values i will use equal to operator. -> 10 == 10

7. Identify the three blocks in this code:
As we know pyhton is indentaion sensitive language we should take care of this while writing code.
spam = 0
if spam == 10:   ----> Firts Block
print('eggs') 
if spam > 5:    -----> Second Block
print('bacon')  
else:           -------> Third Block
print('ham')   
print('spam')
print('spam')

8. Write code that prints Hello if 1 is stored in spam, prints Howdy if 2 is stored in spam, and prints
Greetings! if anything else is stored in spam.

spam = 1
if (spam == 1):
   print("Hello")
elif (spam == 2):
   print("Howdy")
else:
   print("Greetings!")

